text:
Guwa! I don't know if hololive read, or can read, their chat comments. But on the off-chance, to get better with motion sickness, you can do some of the following-

1 - Air travel bracelet (my greatest VR friend). It helps with all motion sickness, through acupressure. Just two cheap little bracelets, I think about $1, put them on and you should feel a little bit better.
2 - Ginger root- also a good friend. Tea, or some ginger biscuits, or something. Ginger root helps relieve nausea of all kinds, I believe. I think the recommendation is an hour or two before using the headset to let it go into your system, but I always just drink it directly beforehand.
3 - In-game settings. The vignette (which appears to be active), and the teleport mode. Teleport might not be ideal, immersion wise, but it helps a lot with motion sickness because it removes that "the world is moving but I am no" sensation.

(EDIT: Putting this before 4;
Move yourself in real life, when you move in VR. Not, physically walk everywhere, but gently sway your arms as if you were walking, and either lift your heels of your feet off the ground to mimic the movement of walking, or lift your feet up and walk on the spot. I've heard this helps a lot, but I can't confirm personally whether it works, like the other points, because I have bad legs and this just hurts me more than it helps me. lol)


4 - Last, the slow one, play a lot of short sessions in peaceful and relaxing games to get yourself used to it. Instead of moving around in the game, find something that lets you move around a little bit in real life, even if it's just a metre (/ a few feet) in each direction. This'll just help adjust you a tiny bit for the VR, and will very slowly ease your mind into the realisation that the word being looked at isn't real.
